===subject:Reply #1
===from:Keith Lewis
===date:Tue Oct  8 19:53:31 2002
===message:In response to Melonie:

   I agree with your position on the causes of war.  The provocation of one nation leads to the entanglement of several regions.  I think history saw this best portrayed in World War I.  The European "powder keg" was set to explode as several countries became entangled among each other through informal treaties.  As soon as the spark was set off--in this case, the assasination of Archduke Ferdinand--the whole continent erupted.  Also, I think this was the main goal of the League of Nations, and subsequently the United Nations.  The idea that a group of countries employ diplomacy and stick up for each other in one big commitment to one another, rather than many small informal treaties is a great movement toward World Peace.
=========yorg=========
